## .NET 8 Migration: `TimedExecutor`

### Key Breaking Changes

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 | Impact |
|---|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** | Hard crash at runtime |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** | Dead code path |
| `ThreadAbortException` | Never thrown | Catch block is unreachable |

`Thread.Abort()` was removed because it corrupts application state — it can fire *mid-instruction*, leaving locks held, `finally` blocks skipped, and objects half-constructed.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Runs <paramref name="work"/> with a cooperative cancellation timeout.
    /// The delegate must observe the CancellationToken to stop promptly.
    /// </summary>
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Block the caller, just like the original thread.Join(timeout) did.
            task.Wait(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }

        // Task.Result re-throws as AggregateException, preserving original behavior.
        return task.Result;
    }

    /// <summary>
    /// Async-native overload — prefer this in new code.
    /// </summary>
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await work(cts.Token).WaitAsync(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### Usage Comparison

```csharp
// OLD — fire-and-forget abort (unsafe)
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    () => SlowQuery(connString),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

// NEW — cooperative cancellation (safe)
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    ct => SlowQuery(connString, ct),   // pass token into the real work
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

// NEW async — preferred
var result = await executor.ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync(
    async ct => await SlowQueryAsync(connString, ct),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### Pitfalls to Watch For

1. **Cooperative cancellation is not automatic.** If `work` ignores the `CancellationToken`, it keeps running after timeout — the thread pool thread is *not* killed. Every I/O call (HTTP, SQL, file) must receive the token.

2. **Legacy "uncanellable" work** — if you truly cannot modify the callee, you can abandon (not abort) it on a background thread, but this **leaks the thread**:

    ```csharp
    // LAST RESORT — leaked thread on timeout, equivalent danger to the original
    public T ExecuteWithTimeoutUncooperative<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        T result = default;
        Exception error = null;

        var thread = new Thread(() =>
        {
            try { result = work(); }
            catch (Exception ex) { error = ex; }
        }) { IsBackground = true };  // won't block process exit

        thread.Start();

        if (!thread.Join(timeout))
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");

        if (error != null)
            throw new AggregateException(error);

        return result;
    }
    ```
    This is strictly worse than the original (thread leaks instead of aborting), so push callers toward the cooperative model.

3. **`Task.Wait()` vs `await`** — the sync overload blocks a thread. Use the async overload everywhere you can to avoid threadpool starvation.

4. **`AggregateException` wrapping** — `Task.Result` already wraps in `AggregateException`, matching the original behavior. If callers expect the inner exception unwrapped, use `task.GetAwaiter().GetResult()` instead.
